1:11	Proceedings of the Workshop on Incremental Parsing: Bringing Engineering and Cognition Together Held in cooperation with ACL-2004 Edited by Frank Keller, Stephen Clark, Matthew Crocker and Mark Steedman 25 July 2004 Barcelona, Spain Order copies of this and other ACL proceedings from: Association for Computational Linguistics (ACL) 73 Landmark Center East Stroudsburg, PA 18301 USA Tel: +1-570-476-8006 Fax: +1-570-476-0860 acl@aclweb.org WORKSHOP ORGANIZERS: Frank Keller, University of Edinburgh Stephen Clark, University of Edinburgh Matthew Crocker, Saarland University Mark Steedman, University of Edinburgh KEYNOTE SPEAKERS: Brian Roark, Oregon Health and Science University Patrick Sturt, University of Glasgow PROGRAM COMMITTEE: Steve Abney, University of Michigan Thorsten Brants, Google Eugene Charniak, Brown University Ciprian Chelba, Microsoft Research Michael Collins, MIT Jeffrey Elman, UCSD Ted Gibson, MIT John Hale, Michigan State University Mark Johnson, Brown University Gerard Kempen, Leiden University Oliver Lemon, University of Edinburgh Massimo Poesio, University of Essex Stefan Riezler, Palo Alto Research Center Brian Roark, Oregon Health and Science University Douglas Roland, UCSD Ed Stabler, UCLA Suzanne Stevenson, University of Toronto Patrick Sturt, University of Glasgow WORKSHOP WEBSITE: http://homepages.inf.ed.ac.uk/keller/acl04 workshop/ INTRODUCTION The papers in these proceedings were presented at the ACL-2004 workshop Incremental Parsing: Bringing Engineering and Cognition Together, held in Barcelona on July 25.
2:11	Incremental processing is crucial for many NLP tasks.
3:11	Language modelling, for instance, typically requires that probabilities are assigned incrementally as more and more of the speech stream becomes available.
4:11	Also, there is substantial evidence showing that humans process language in an incremental fashion, and thus any cognitively plausible model of human parsing must take incrementality into account.
5:11	The aim of the workshop was to address the dual challenge of defining incremental parsing models that are useful for engineering tasks such as language modelling, while also contributing to our understanding and modelling of the human parsing mechanism.
6:11	We were pleased to receive 20 submissions, of which we accepted 8 papers for presentation and 3 as reserve papers.
7:11	Both elements of the workshop theme are well-represented in the proceedings, with roughly 6 of the papers relating to NLP/language engineering, and 5 relating to cognitive modelling.
8:11	We would like to thank the program committee for the excellent job they did in reviewing the submissions.
9:11	As well as 8 paper presentations, we also had talks from two keynote speakers: Brian Roark, from the Oregon Graduate Institute, Oregon Health and Science University, and Patrick Sturt, from the Department of Psychology, University of Glasgow.
10:11	The proceedings include extended abstracts for these talks.
